            COMMENTEMAILMORESAN FRANCISCO  — Ford is planning for success in a future with more congestion, fewer cars and fewer people driving them.Instead of fighting public transportation, bicycles and car-sharing services, Ford is looking to join them. And still make money even if fewer people are buying cars.Ford is trying to reinvent itself as a mobility company and address the trend in urban areas of cities growing and becoming more congested, CEO Mark Fields said in an interview. "People value access more than ownership. We need to understand customers' concerns and make their lives easier."Related: Ford cars will see around cornersIn researching ways for people to share the road and forms of transportation and individual vehicles, Ford hopes to uncover business opportunities along the way. Fields said the company is pivoting from just products to offering more services to make life and mobility easier."We are testing the thesis of satisfying demand and make money at it," Fields said from San Francisco. The concept is that making peoples' lives better is good business and if, decades from now, the world is buying fewer vehicles, Ford wants to have a big slice of that smaller pie.Related: Ford's next step to making autonomous driving a realityBuy Photo (Photo: Detroit Free Press)As the automaker takes research projects into autonomous driving and starts to implement them, Ford is also piloting some car sharing programs, CEO Mark Fields announced in a speech at the automaker's Research and Innovation Center in Palo Alto Tuesday.It is part of the larger Ford Smart Mobility plan that incorporates connectivity, mobility, autonomous vehicles and big data. Ford introduced the plan in January, along with 25 experiments aimed at better understanding consumers' mobility needs around the globe."My great-grandfather helped put the world on wheels so everyone could enjoy the benefits of mobility," said Ford Executive Chairman Bill Ford in a statement.  "Our vision today is to expand that same thinking using advanced technology and new business models, and addressing the mobility challenges people face around the world."After gathering data and consumer insights for six months, Ford is using that data to proceed in two areas: car sharing and alternative ways of getting around increasingly congested cities where many forms of transportation share the road.Ford Motor Credit will team with two car-sharing companies: Getaround in the U.S. and easyCar Club in London. The idea is a customer can rent a car that was financed through Ford Credit to pre-screened clients.The Peer-2-Peer Car Sharing pilot program will run through November and involve 14,000 customers in six U.S. cities who will use Getaround software.  It will be offered to customers in Berkeley, Oakland and San Francisco in California; as well as in Portland, Oregon; Chicago and Washington, D.C. It runs through November.Related: Mark Fields earns $18.6M in first year as Ford CEOBuy Photo (Photo: Alisa Priddle, Detroit Free Press)Fields is hoping the program will make Ford owners more loyal customers and expose those who don't own a car to what Ford has to offer for when they are in the market."It will raise awareness and is a bridge to ownership," Fields said.Another 12,000 Ford owners in London will use easyCar Club to rent out their car.  It is a way to offset monthly payments."Consumers tell us they are interested in sharing the costs of vehicle ownership, and this program will help us understand how much that extends to customers who are financing a Ford vehicle," said David McClelland, Ford Credit vice president of marketing. "As most vehicles are parked and out of use much of the time, this can help us gauge our customers' desires to pick up extra cash and keep their vehicles in use."A third of millennials are interested in renting out their own belongings to supplement their income, according to independent researchers Penn Schoen Berland. And they say after lending a book, a car is the item they are most open to sharing and half are open to the idea.Half of millennial and Generation Z consumers say they would share a car for the cost savings; 40% say it is a good way to try a new product.Buy Photo (Photo: Alisa Priddle/Detroit Free Press)And Ford will participate in an Uber-like model with GoDrive, an on-demand car sharing pilot in London where you order a car and pay for a one-way trip with guaranteed parking. There will be 50 cars positioned in 20 locations available for pay-as-you-go, per-minute pricing in cars such as the Focus Electric car.As part of the research into how people get around today, Ford is introducing a new electric bike concept, MoDe:Flex, and an extension of the MoDe:Link prototype smartphone app to use the ebike. The app provides real-time information on weather, congestion, parking costs, time, traffic and public transportation as well as navigation, route planning, and health and fitness information.There is even a version of the app for the smartwatch.Fields did not rule out making ebikes in the future, if the research suggests that is a viable business to pursue."We now are moving from experimentation to implementation," said Fields. "We have learned a lot in the past six months, and now are ready to put insights into action. Our goal is to make people's lives better by helping them more easily navigate through their day, address societal issues and, over time, change the way the world moves – just as Henry Ford did more than 100 years ago."Contact Alisa Priddle: 313-222-5394 or apriddle@freepress.com. Follow her on Twitter @AlisaPriddle
            
